          "title": "Tears at the altar: when worship cannot substitute for faithfulness",
          "body": "Verse 13 names a scene that should arrest every reader: the men of Judah are covering the altar with tears, weeping and groaning, because God no longer accepts their offerings. Their emotional intensity is beyond question. But God refuses the offerings, and the next verse names why: the same men weeping at the altar have dealt treacherously with the wives of their youth (2:14). The Lord has been a witness between each man and the wife he married — the marriage covenant was made before God, and God holds it. The tears are real; the grief is real; the worship is real. And none of it substitutes for covenant faithfulness to the woman who is 'your companion and your wife by covenant' (2:14). Malachi anticipates Jesus's teaching in Matthew 5:23-24: the offering must wait when the relationship is broken. God does not receive worship from hands that have committed domestic treachery, no matter how wetly those hands are raised at the altar."
