        "excerpt": "For the lips of a priest should preserve knowledge, and men should seek instruction from his mouth; for he is the messenger of the Lord of hosts.",
        "body": "The opening oracle (2:1-9) is structurally a covenant lawsuit. God is the plaintiff, the priests are the defendant, and the evidence is the gap between Levi's original covenant (2:4-6) and the present priesthood's conduct (2:7-9). The lawsuit opens with a condition: 'If you do not listen, and if you do not take it to heart to give honor to My name' (2:2). Both verbs are conditional — 'listen' (*shama*) and 'take to heart' (*sum lev*) — which together describe inward reception, not merely external compliance. The priests are hearing the words of the commandment but not allowing those words to form them. This is precisely the diagnostic that Ezekiel identified in the generation of the exile: 'They hear your words but they do not do them' (Ezekiel 33:31-32).\n\nGod's announced consequence is dramatic: He will curse their blessings (2:2). The Aaronic benediction of Numbers 6:24-26 — the very words the priests pronounced over Israel — will be reversed at their source. God is not withdrawing blessing passively; He is actively transforming the priests' benedictions into curses. The imagery escalates at verse 3: God will spread the refuse (*peresh*) of the festival sacrifices on their faces. The entrails and dung of the animals removed from the sanctuary as unclean (Exodus 29:14; Leviticus 4:11-12) will be smeared on the priests themselves. They are being identified with what they have treated the altar's offerings as — waste.\n\nThe positive standard (2:5-6) is set against this judgment with deliberate pastoral intention. Levi's covenant was characterized by *life and peace* — terms that together evoke the full-orbed blessing of covenant relationship: vitality (*chay*) and wholeness (*shalom*). The ideal Levi did not merely perform rituals correctly; he *walked with God* (2:6), a phrase used of the most intimate divine-human fellowship in the Old Testament. His instruction was not only accurate but morally aligned: 'true instruction was in his mouth and unrighteousness was not found on his lips.' The two sides of the mouth — what it says and what it refuses to say — were both consecrated.\n\nVerse 7 then names the priestly calling at its theological apex: the priest is 'the messenger of the LORD of hosts.' *Maleakh* — the same word as Malachi's name, the same word for angelic messengers. The priest stands at the boundary between God and people as a divine envoy. Douglas Moo (writing on the Levitical parallel in Hebrews) notes that this designation makes the priest's teaching office functionally prophetic: to receive instruction from the priest's mouth is to receive it from God. This makes the corruption of 2:8 proportionally catastrophic. The priest who was to preserve knowledge has instead caused many to stumble. The community's fallenness in chapters 2:10-3:15 is, in part, the harvest of corrupted teaching.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Torah* (instruction/law) occurs four times in 2:6-9, always in relation to the priestly mouth — what it teaches. *Maleakh* (messenger, 2:7) is the book's title-word; the priest is a living embodiment of the prophet's own role. *Kashal* (stumble, 2:8) is used by Isaiah and Ezekiel for national collapse under failed leadership. *Shachat* (corrupted, 2:8) is used of the pre-flood corruption in Genesis 6:12 — the same depth of defilement."
